LXXXVII. ΟΧ ΡΑΤΚΙΟΚ BLACKIE'S GARDEN, THE ROYAL TAILOR.

The sartorial art comes to w'e with the pictorial. even of Nature herself. Much of the descriptions here of flowers and fruits is found also in the poems under No. LIII.

ARGUMENT.

This is Blackie‘s garden, lying amid mountains and waves, far away under the extreme axis of the sky. Blue violets one may gather, silver lilies amid golden roses, pinks and narcissi, fresh aquilegia and hyacinth, paeonies and poppies, flos Adonis and amaranth, tulips too and iris, myrfles, and laurels and winter-roses. Fruits likewise bloom, pears and figs and mul- berries, cherries, quinces and citrons. Here you have Alcinous’ grove, Adonis’ gardens‚ and all the products of the Hesperides. O foolish Nature, be not too proud of thyself. Art and the owner's cunning [sartorial] needle have produced this painted scene.
